The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, August 06, 2004  Corporate Briefs																								 Wipro has sought 85 acres of land for expansion near its facility in Chennai and about 25 acres for setting up a new facility in Coimbatore, Tamil Nadu IT secretary Vivek Harinarain said. Wipro chief Azim Premji indicated that the companys workforce in Chennai would expand from 5,000 to 25,000 over a period, he added. According to Harinarain, Tamil Nadu has continuity of policy and low attrition in the IT and ITES sectors  advantages which current infotech hub Bangalore lacks.																								 Nicholas Piramal India Ltd (NPIL), a pharma major, has signed an in-licensing agreement with the US-based Genzyme Corporation for synvisc viscose supplementation for the Indian market, enhancing the formers presence in the orthopaedics sector. The in-licensing agreement is an exclusive five-year alliance, NPIL informed the Bombay Stock Exchange.																								 ICICI Infotech Ltd has formed an alliance with Eurobase Systems, a software and services supplier in the global banking and insurance markets. Under the deal, Eurobase would integrate ICICI Infotechs flagship Kastle, a back-office treasury system, and Riskfree, a market risk analysis system, with its treasury dealing system Siena.																								 The Delhi-based Real Electricals Pvt Ltd (REPL), maker of consumer electronics appliances, has opened a Calcutta office. Its products include voltage stabilisers, geysers, toasters, emergency lights and exhaust fans.																								 HDFC Bank has opened eight new branches in Delhi, taking its total branches to 340 across the nation. The number of branches went up to 124 in northern India.																								 Raymond Ltd has received shareholders approval at its annual general meeting in Mumbai to distribute a 55 per cent dividend for the fiscal ended June 30, 2004.																								 Punjab National Bank (PNB) has opened an overseas branch in Kabul after obtaining approvals from Afghanistans central bank. The branch will maintain deposits in dollar and Afghani currencies and will provide loans for personal and business purposes, a bank release said.																								 Bajaj Auto will raise the production of CT-100 motorcycles to 2,000 per month from August. With the current production of 1,400 motorcycles per month, the sales had already crossed one lakh units in 81 days, area assistant sales manager T. Balasubramaniam said.																								 Cartier, a renowned jewellery house, has launched Declaration, a gold watch with diamond settings, priced between Rs 1.65 lakh and Rs 8 lakh. ADVERTISEMENT
